title: As Election Draws Near, The Stock Market Holds Strong
text: Friday gave the thrill of a roller coaster ride, as we watched the major stock market indices run up and down throughout the day.  While it's not the ride most investors look for in the stock market, it's the best they can get since most amusement parks have yet to re-open.

title: S&P 500 Trading Outlook: Cycles Point To Post-Election Weakness
text: Trends from the past week remain negative, yet the lack of a meaningful breakdown in the U.S. stock market offers some reasons for optimism. And, although cycles point sharply lower after the presidential election, there could be one final move higher for stocks in the next week.

title: Cries for more stimulus are overblown and stock investors should stop throwing ‘tantrums' about it, says a Wall Street chief strategist
text: Amplified calls for more fiscal stimulus ignore the economic recovery's current strength, James Paulsen, chief investment strategist at The Leuthold Group, said Thursday. Investors, executives, and lawmakers have spent recent weeks clamoring for a new bill, warning that failure to pass fresh stimulus endangers the nation's rebound. Federal Reserve Chairman Jerome Powell emphasized in early October that passing too much aid posed fewer risks than passing too little. President Donald Trump has repeatedly called for a bill even larger than the $2.2 trillion CARES Act.

title: Housing Gets Hotter
text: U.S. equity markets were mixed this week as better-than-expected economic data and strong corporate earnings results were offset by continued coronavirus concerns and frustration over the ongoing stimulus stalemate. Snapping a three-week winning streak, the S&P 500 ended the week lower by 0.4%, but remains within 4% of its all-time highs. Technology stocks remained under pressure amid an ongoing censorship controversy.

title: Rising rates seem to signal a recovery is near, but investors wonder whether they can be believed
text: Yields rolled to a four-month high last week, the 10-year note reaching 0.84%, as economic data continue to arrive better than expected.

title: Market Snapshot: Stock-market investors brace for busiest week of earnings in October's final hurrah
text: The S&P 500's tech giants will vie for attention as they barrage the market with third-quarter earnings in the week before the Nov. 3 election.

title: Stocks will see a big surge in the 1st quarter of 2021 after stimulus passes, forecasts billionaire investor Paul Tudor Jones
text: Billionaire investor Paul Tudor Jones told CNBC on Thursday the stock market could see a large gain in the beginning of 2021 after the next stimulus is passed.  "At some point in the first quarter next year you're going to have a big move to the upside from whatever level that might be, as people get cash from this first stimulus program and they deploy that in a variety of financial assets," Jones said.

title: Will The U.S. Avoid Eurozone's Rising Double-Dip Recession Risk?

title: 'The road to financial implosion': A notorious market bear says the Fed has set the stage for a 67% stock plunge — and warns of zero-to-negative returns over the next 12 years
text: If it's a rosy outlook for stocks you're searching for, it's safe to say that John Hussman — the outspoken investor and former professor who's been predicting a stock-market collapse — isn't about to deliver. "There is a particular lesson that history regularly teaches, yet the public never actually learns," he penned in a recent client note.

title: Looking Beyond The Wall Of Worry
text: Markets hate uncertainty, but that's about to change as we will soon know who will be president in a few weeks.

title: Here are 5 ways investors should position their portfolios if Joe Biden wins, according to a top investment strategist
text: Investors across the globe are considering making changes to their portfolios and evaluating their exposure to ensure they are correctly positioned ahead of what promises to be a volatile US election. Most are increasingly pricing in a Biden victory and a blue-wave outcome as the Democratic presidential nominee maintains a hefty lead in the polls. However, JPMorgan says markets may be too quick in expecting a Biden presidency as narrowing odds could lead to a contested election.
